Additionally, the KOH-controlled hydrothermal modification of metallic Ti also involves the formation of some K-polytitanates. This is manifested by the dissolution of Ti into the aqueous KOH solution to form some polytitanate anions, and, depending on the hydrothermal conditions as well as the KOH concentration, these polytitanate anions are then precipitated in the form of K-polytitanates onto the titania surface. This K-polytitanate formation can be represented as38,39:32mKOH+2nHOH→2mK++2(n+m)OH−+2nH+(hydrolysis)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
